<h3>Content</h3>
<pre>
********************************************************************************
// SECTION 1 INTRODUCTION
********************************************************************************
cd "-working directory-"	// This changes the working directory for the session.
							// e.g.
							// cd "H:\EFN508\Stata\"

**********************************************


// Exercise 1 {Visualise}


**********************************************
// 1. Normal distributions
* The -quietly- command, which suppresses output in stata, can be abbreviated to -qui-.
clear
set seed 456
qui set obs 1000000

// Generate z and z1
* the -generate- command can be abbreviated to -g-.
g z		=	rnormal()
g z1	=	rnormal(3,4)

// Plot histograms
* Plot a histogram, and include the kernel density as an option (after the comma).
hist z,	kdensity	title("Drawn from z~N(0,1)")	// -histogram- is abbreviated as -hist-
hist z1,kdensity	title("Drawn from z~N(3,4)")


		
// 2. Chi-squared
// Generate the random variable.
g c1	=	rchi2(10)

// Plot histogram
hist c1,kdensity	title("Drawn from chi-squared with 10 degrees of freedom")



// 3. t-distribution
// Generate random variable (t-distribution with 10 degrees of freedom)
* Note, the degrees of freedom here depend on the degrees of freedom of the donominator chi-squared distribution.
g t1	=	z/sqrt(c1/10)
// Plot histogram
hist t1, kdensity	title("Drawn from t-distribution with 10 degrees of freedom")



// 4. F-distribution
// Generate random variable (f1~F(1,10))
g f1	=	t1^2
hist f1, kdensity	title("Drawn from F(1,10)")



**********************************************


// Exercise 2 {US Macroeconomic Data}


**********************************************
// 1. Import data
import excel "US Macroeconomic Data.xls", sheet("Sheet1") firstrow clear
* The text inside the quotation marks -"- should include the directory in which the data is stored.
* Importing can also be done via File>Import

// 2. Generate "dates" series
g dates	=	1963+_n-1	// This sets the first observation (n=1) as 1963,
						// and each subsequent observation as 1963+n-1.
tsset dates, yearly		// This makes "dates" a set of annual time series data.

// 3. Save the dataset
save "US Macroeconomic Data"	// The dataset will be saved to the working directory



**********************************************


// Exercise 3 {Australian Business Cycle}


**********************************************
// 1. Import data
import excel "gdp.xlsx", sheet("gdp.xls") firstrow clear

// 2. Create dates vector
g dates	=	tq(1959q2)+_n-1	// Creates quarterly dates vector beginning from 1959q2
							// See http://www.stata.com/manuals13/ddatetime.pdf 
tsset dates,quarterly		// Declares the vector a quarterly time series

// 3. Calculate annual percentage growth rate
g G		=	100*( log(gdp) - log(L4.gdp) )
* The -L4.- operator summons the 4th lag in the dataset.
* In other words, G(t)=100*( log( gdp(t) ) - log( gdp(t-4) ) )
* The 4th lag is used because the data is quarterly.

// 4. Compute Australian business cycle by smoothing G using seventh order moving average
g BCYCLE	=	( L3.G + L2.G + L1.G + G + F1.G + F2.G + F3.G ) / 7
// -L.- is a lag operator and -F.- is a lead operator

// 5. Plot G and BCYCLE on same graph
twoway (line G dates) (line BCYCLE dates)
* Alternatively, use -tsline G BCYCLE-

/*
NOTE: IT IS SOMETIMES USEFUL TO PLOT IN BLACK AND WHITE
To do so, enter command -set scheme s2mono- before plotting a graph.
For example:

	set scheme s2mono
	twoway (line G dates) (line BCYCLE dates)

For more information, see http://www.stata.com/help.cgi?schemes	
*/

**********************************************


// Exercise 4 {Plotting Time Series Data}


**********************************************
import delimited "taylor.csv",clear

// 1. Create date vector
g year	=	tq(1961q1)+_n-1
tsset year,quarterly

// 2. Plot time series on one graph
tsline ffr infl ygap, legend(order (1 "ffr" 2 "infl" 3 "infl"))	// -tsline- plots a time series line using the defined time series vector

// 3. Combine separate plots
gr drop all		// -gr- is an abbreviation of -graphs-
				// This command drops all graphs stored in memory
twoway (tsline infl), name(pl_infl)	// Store thie graph in memory as "pl_infl"
twoway (tsline ygap), name(pl_ygap)	// Store thie graph in memory as "pl_ygap"
twoway (tsline ffr), name (pl_ffr)	// Store thie graph in memory as "pl_ffr"
gr combine pl_infl pl_ygap pl_ffr	// Combine the stored graphs



**********************************************


// Exercise 5 {Basic Descriptive Statistics}


**********************************************
use "food.dta"

// 1. Provide summary and descriptive statistics
sum			// The -summarize- command can be abbreviated to -su-
d			// The -describe- command can be abbreviated to -d-

// 2. Draw histograms of food_exp and income
hist food_exp
hist income

// 3. Draw box plots of food_exp and income
graph box food_exp
graph box income

// 4. Draw scatterplot of food_exp versus income
twoway (scatter food_exp income)



**********************************************


// Exercise 6 {U.S. Consumption and Income}


**********************************************
* This data is online. Set the online path, then access datasets from there.
webuse set http://www.ncer.edu.au/stata-resources/data/Honours/
webuse "cons_us.dta",clear

// Create date vector
g dates	=	tq(1970q1)+_n-1
tsset dates, quarterly

// 1. Construct first log difference of consumption and plot
g rcons	=	log(cons) - log(L1.cons)
tsline rcons

// 2. Construct 5th and 7th order moving averages of rcons series
// 5th order MA
g bcycle5	=	(L2.rcons + L1.rcons + rcons + F1.rcons + F2.rcons) / 5
// 7th order MA
g bcycle7	=	(L3.rcons + L2.rcons + L1.rcons + rcons + F1.rcons + F2.rcons + F3.rcons) / 7
// Plot
tsline rcons bcycle5 bcycle7, name(pl_cons)

// 3. Use rinc
g rinc	=	log(inc)-log(L1.inc)
tsline rinc rcons
g bcycleinc5	=	(L2.rinc + L1.rinc + rinc + F1.rinc + F2.rinc) / 5
g bcycleinc7	=	(L3.rinc + L2.rinc + L1.rinc + rinc + F1.rinc + F2.rinc +F3.rinc) / 5
tsline rinc bcycleinc5 bcycleinc7, name(pl_inc)

gr combine pl_cons pl_inc

// 4. Calculate percentage growth rates
g g_rcons	=	100*rcons
g g_rinc	=	100*rinc
// Compute descriptive statistics
su rcons rinc

// 5. Perform scatter plot
twoway (scatter g_rcons g_rinc), title(Consumption/Income)

// 6. Compute correlation
cor g_rcons g_rinc

// 7. Calculate savings ratio
g ratio	=	( income-cons ) / income
// Plot savings ratio
tsline ratio

// 8. Compute descriptive statistics on savings ratio
su ratio

// 9. Plot histogram of savings ratio
hist ratio, title(Savings Ratio)
// For more options, see http://www.stata.com/manuals13/rhistogram.pdf
// For example, the number of bins/intervals can be changed
// e.g. -hist ratio, bin(20) title(Savings Ratio)-

</pre>
</li>
